description: From Middle English upheven, from Old English ūphebban, ūpāhebban (“to lift up, raise up, exalt, rise in the air, fly”), equivalent to up- +‎ heave. Cognate with Dutch opheffen (“to lift, raise”), German aufheben (“to lift, raise, cancel, repeal”).

verbs.description: upheave (third-person singular simple present upheaves, present participle upheaving, simple past upheaved or uphove, past participle upheaved or uphoven)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To heave or lift up; raise up or aloft.
(transitive) To lift or thrust something upward forcefully, or be similarly lifted or thrust upward.
